On a fresh installation of Docker on an Ubuntu Server or a Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) server, Docker does not always start automatically after a system reboot by default.
Whether it starts automatically depends entirely on how the package manager configured the service during installation:
Ubuntu Server: The official installation package usually automatically enables and starts the Docker service upon installation.
RHEL: Following RHEL's strict security-first philosophy, services are intentionally left disabled after installation. You must explicitly tell the system to allow Docker to boot on startup.
Fortunately, both flavors use the exact same modern initialization framework called systemd to handle background services.
1. How to make Docker start automatically on both flavors
To ensure Docker always boots up whenever your Ubuntu or RHEL server restarts, run the following command in your terminal:
Bash
sudo systemctl enable docker.service
If you also want to enable the Docker Application Container Engine socket (which allows the Docker CLI to communicate with the daemon immediately upon boot), run this as well:
Bash
sudo systemctl enable docker.socket
2. How it works behind the scenes (systemd)
When you run systemctl enable docker.service, you are interacting with systemd, the system and service manager that modern Linux operating systems use to boot up. Here is what happens under the hood:
Creating Symlinks (The Hook): Inside the Docker service configuration file (/lib/systemd/system/docker.service), there is a section called [Install] containing the line WantedBy=multi-user.target. When you enable the service, systemd creates a symbolic link (a shortcut) to the Docker service inside the system's startup directory (/etc/systemd/system/multi-user.target.wants/).
The Boot Sequence: When your server restarts and passes the initial kernel phase, it enters the multi-user.target state (the normal command-line network state for a server).
Daemon Activation: systemd scans that multi-user.target.wants directory, finds the shortcut for Docker, and launches the core Docker daemon process (dockerd).
⚠️ Bonus Production Tip: What about the containers?
Enabling the Docker service only ensures that the Docker engine turns on when the server boots. It does not automatically turn your containers back on.
If you want your specific application containers (like a database or web server) to restart automatically whenever the physical Linux server restarts, you must apply a Restart Policy to the containers when you run them.
Add --restart unless-stopped or --restart always to your docker commands:
Bash
# Example for a new container
docker run -d --restart unless-stopped -p 3000:3000 my-app-image
# Example to update an already running container
docker update --restart unless-stopped <container_name_or_id>
unless-stopped: If the server crashes or reboots, Docker will automatically spin this container back up. However, if you manually run docker stop, Docker will respect your command and leave it off during the next reboot.
Docker Buildx is a powerful Docker CLI plugin that completely supercharges how you build container images. 
1. What is Buildx? (The Engine Under the Hood)
Traditionally, when you ran docker build, Docker used a legacy, sequential builder engine.
Buildx acts as a modern replacement that leverages BuildKit. BuildKit is a next-generation build toolkit that replaces the old Docker backend.
Note: In modern versions of Docker (v23.0 and newer), standard docker build is actually just a shortcut (alias) pointing to docker buildx build behind the scenes.
2. Why Use Buildx? (The Key Game-Changers)
🌍 A. Multi-Platform Builds (No more architecture crashes!)
This is Buildx's superpower. If you build an image on an Apple Silicon Mac (ARM64) and try to run it on an Intel/AMD cloud server (AMD64), it will crash.
Buildx allows you to build one image that natively supports multiple CPU architectures simultaneously with a single command:
# docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 -t myusername/my-app:latest --push .
When a user pulls myusername/my-app:latest, Docker automatically detects their CPU and downloads only the version of the image compiled for their specific chip! 
B. Parallel Layer Compilation & Smarter Caching
Parallel Processing: The old Docker builder read your Dockerfile sequentially (Step 1, then Step 2, then Step 3). BuildKit creates a dependency tree. If you are compiling a backend and a frontend in a multi-stage Dockerfile, Buildx runs those builds at the same time.
Remote Cache Sharing: Buildx allows you to export your build cache straight to a container registry (using --cache-to and --cache-from). This means your CI/CD pipelines (like GitHub Actions) can pull cache layers directly from the cloud instead of rebuilding your entire app from scratch on every single commit.
C. Secure Build-Time Secrets
In the past, if you needed an API key or an SSH key to download private packages during a build, you had to pass it as a build-arg. The massive security flaw here is that those arguments get permanently baked into the image history for anyone to see.
Buildx introduces Mount Secrets:
# Inside your Dockerfile
RUN --mount=type=secret,id=my_secret_key npm install
This safely mounts your local secret file into the container only during that specific build step. Once the build finishes, the secret is completely erased, leaving absolutely no trace in the final image history. 
Step 1: Create a Custom Builder
The default builder instance doesn't support complex tasks like multi-platform building. You must create an isolated builder instance (using the docker-container driver):
# docker buildx create --name my-advanced-builder --use
The --use flag sets this new builder as your default engine. 
Step 2: Bootstrap the Builder
Initialize the builder so it spins up the background BuildKit environment:
# docker buildx inspect –bootstrap
Step 3: Check your Available Platforms
Run this command to see what architectures your new builder is capable of compiling for:
# docker buildx ls
You will see a clean list displaying all compatible platforms (such as linux/amd64, linux/arm64, linux/riscv64, etc.). 
4. A Simple Workflow Example
Let's look at how you would build and deploy a multi-platform app:
# 1. Log in to your registry (e.g., Docker Hub)
# docker login
# 2. Build for both Intel (amd64) and Apple/Raspberry Pi (arm64) and push
# docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 -t abdulsalamkp2003/my-app:v1.0 --push .
⚠️ A Crucial Note on the --push flag: When you build for multiple architectures, Docker cannot load the resulting multi-arch image directly into your local computer's standard single-architecture image store. Therefore, you must use --push to send it directly to Docker Hub (where the manifest index is compiled), OR if you just want to test locally on your own machine, replace --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 with your native local architecture and swap --push with --load. 
1. What is a CI/CD Runner?
A Runner is simply an isolated, dedicated computer (a Virtual Machine, a physical server, or a Docker container) that runs a specialized background agent.
The Core Concept: Git platforms (like GitHub or GitLab) are just the "brains" that store your code and parse your .github/workflows or .gitlab-ci.yml files. They do not actually run your tests or compile your code.
The Agent: When a pipeline is triggered, the Git platform sends instructions to a Runner Agent. The runner receives the commands, executes them locally (like running npm install or docker build), and sends the logs and results back to your dashboard.
2. Step-by-Step: Why We Need Runners
Without a runner, your CI/CD pipeline is just a text file. Let's look at why they are absolutely essential through a typical code change lifecycle:
[Developer pushes code] ──> [Git Server (GitHub/GitLab)] ──> [Dispatches Job] ──> [Runner Executing commands]
🔁 Step 1: Clean Isolation (Preventing the "Works on My Machine" Syndrome)
When you test code on your local computer, it relies on your local databases, globally installed packages, and specific environment variables. A Runner provides a clean, reproducible, and isolated environment for every single run. It pulls your code into a fresh environment to prove it actually works without "local helper files."
⚡ Step 2: Offloading Expensive Compute
Compiling heavy Java/C++ applications, running massive integration test suites, or building large Docker images requires massive amounts of CPU and RAM.
If the central Git server tried to process thousands of developer builds directly on its own hardware, it would instantly crash under the load.
Runners act as decentralized workers. You can scale them up horizontally to handle massive parallel workloads.
🔐 Step 3: Security & Network Access (Crucial for Self-Hosting)
Imagine you want your CI/CD pipeline to deploy an app onto your secure private AWS EC2 instance in a private subnet.
If you use a public cloud CI/CD tool, it can't reach your server because of your firewall.
By installing a Self-Hosted Runner inside your private network, the runner can securely poll the Git server over HTTPS, pull the code, and deploy it locally without opening any inbound firewall ports to the public internet!
3. How Packages are "Prepacked" in Runners
When you run a job, you expect tools like git, docker, python, node, or aws-cli to be instantly available. There are three main ways these packages are delivered inside runners:
Way A: The Hosted "Omnibus" VM Image (e.g., GitHub-hosted Ubuntu)
If you use standard GitHub-hosted runners (runs-on: ubuntu-latest), you are using VMs prepacked with hundreds of gigabytes of developer tools.
The Build Pipeline: Behind the scenes, GitHub and GitLab use tools like HashiCorp Packer to automate the creation of virtual machine images (AMIs or VMDKs).
Pre-installing everything: The packer scripts spin up a blank OS, run massive scripts to pre-install dozens of versions of Node.js, Python, Java, Docker, Go, and database CLI tools, and then "freeze" that disk image.
Instant Ephemeral Boot: When your job triggers, a hypervisor instantly clones that frozen, prepacked virtual disk image into a brand-new VM, giving you access to all those pre-installed packages in seconds.
Way B: The Docker Executor (Dynamic Packing)
If you are using a Docker-based runner (very common in GitLab CI), the runner machine itself is totally blank except for the Docker Engine.
Inside your pipeline file, you specify an image: image: node:20 or image: python:3.11.
The runner downloads that highly lightweight, pre-configured official Docker image on the fly.
The runner spins up a container using that image and executes your code inside it. This is incredibly fast and keeps your base runner machine lightweight and clean.
Way C: Self-Hosted Bare Metal
If you manage your own physical server or VM, nothing is pre-packed. You are responsible for logging in and running sudo apt install nodejs or whatever dependencies your app requires before running your pipeline.
4. The History of Runners: From Cron Jobs to Kubernetes
The evolution of runners mirrors the overall evolution of DevOps over the last 20 years:
2000s: Cron Jobs & Bash ──> 2011: Jenkins Master/Agent ──> 2015: Ephemeral Containers ──> 2020+: Kubernetes Autoscaling


Era 1: Pre-Runner Era (Early 2000s)
Before dedicated CI engines, developers wrote custom shell scripts triggered by cron jobs on a shared testing server. There was no real isolation—if developer A's test crashed the server or corrupted a database, developer B's tests broke too.
Era 2: The Jenkins Master-Agent Era (2011)
Jenkins popularized the concept of "Master and Slaves" (now called Controller and Agents).
The Jenkins controller kept the UI, and physical "Agent" servers ran the build tasks.
The drawback: These agents were persistent virtual machines. If a build modified files or left background processes running, the next build would inherit that "dirty" state, leading to unpredictable testing results.
Era 3: The Dedicated Runner Era (2014–2018)
With the launch of GitLab Runner (written in Go) and Azure Pipelines Agent (which GitHub later forked in 2019 to build the GitHub Actions Runner), runners became highly standardized binaries.
They introduced robust Docker executors. Instead of running code directly on the host machine, every pipeline job ran inside a brand-new, clean Docker container and was completely destroyed afterward.
Era 4: Ephemeral Autoscaling (Current Era)
Instead of keeping 20 VMs running 24/7 (which is incredibly expensive), modern environments utilize Kubernetes and tools like ARC (Actions Runner Controller).
When you push code, a Kubernetes pod (acting as a runner) is instantly created.
It executes your job, pushes the logs, and is immediately terminated, ensuring absolute security, clean states, and zero wasted server costs.
5. How Runners Work: Configuration & Communication
Modern runner architectures are designed to be extremely secure by using a Pull Model.
The Security Flow
Runners never listen for incoming connections. You do not need to open any ports on your runner's firewall. Instead:
Long Polling: The Runner Agent on your machine establishes an outbound HTTPS connection to GitHub/GitLab and asks: "Do you have any jobs for me?"
Authentication: When you initially set up the runner, you provide it with a unique secure token generated by your Git platform.
Execution: If a job is available, the Git server hands the job payload to the runner. The runner executes it, streams the logs back, and returns to waiting.
A Look inside the Configurations
A. GitHub Actions (Self-Hosted Runner config)
