At its absolute simplest, a multi-stage build is like using a temporary kitchen counter to chop, cook, and prep your food, but only taking the final plated meal over to the dining table.
Here is the simple theory behind it:
1. The Core Idea: Splitting "Build" from "Run"
A standard Dockerfile uses a single base image. This means all the heavy machinery used to build your app (compilers, raw source code, test suites, package managers) gets permanently trapped inside the final image.
A multi-stage build allows you to use multiple FROM statements in a single Dockerfile. Each FROM statement starts a brand-new, isolated environment called a Stage:
Stage 1 (The Builder): A big, heavy container filled with all the tools needed to compile or bundle your code.
Stage 2 (The Runner): An ultra-lightweight, minimal container that only has the bare essentials needed to execute your program.
2. The Magic Bridge: COPY --from
The secret weapon of a multi-stage build is the ability to cherry-pick files from a previous stage using the --from flag:
COPY --from=builder /where/the/built/file/is /where/to/put/it/now
DockerfYou throw away Stage 1 entirely, taking only the final compiled executable or folder with you into Stage 2.
3. The 3 Main Benefits
Tiny Image Size: Your final image drops from gigabytes to megabytes because it leaves the heavy build tools behind.
Better Security: By deleting tools like compilers (gcc, npm) and command-line shells (bash) from your final production container, hackers have no built-in tools to use if they manage to break in.
Fast Downloads: Tiny images pull down from your cloud registry to your servers in seconds, making deployments incredibly fast.
